1 (d) (e) the historic or heritage value related to the state of Montana;
2 (e) (f) the successful track record or experience of the organization directing the project;
3 (f) the expected ongoing economic benefit to the state as a result of the project completion;
4 (g) the degree of local contribution to the project;and
5 (h) (g) the anticipated public benefit, including the extent the site or building will be open to the public
6 and the degree of immediate facility use after project completion; and
7 (h) the degree of local contribution to the project. For-profit entities must provide a match equal to
8 $1 for every $1 of grant funding received.
9 (4) The department of commerce shall adopt rules necessary to implement the historic
10 preservation grant program. In adopting rules, the department shall look to the rules adopted for the Montana
11 coal endowment program, the cultural and aesthetic grant program, and other similar state programs. To the
12 extent feasible, the department shall make the rules compatible with those other programs.
13 (5) Government applicants shall comply with Article II, sections 8 and 9, of the Montana
14 constitution and with Title 2, chapter 3, parts 1 and 2, and Title 7. Nongovernment applicants are exempt from
15 this provision."
